#!/usr/bin/env -S uv run --script
# /// script
# requires-python = ">=3.11"
# dependencies = [
#     "httpx>=0.27",
# ]
# ///
"""
windmill — agent-first CLI for a Windmill instance (scripts, schedules, jobs, vars).

This tool is designed to be invoked by agents. Run `windmill help` to load the
full usage contract on demand — do not rely on memorised knowledge of its surface.
It is identity-free: it knows nothing about any consuming project. Connection +
workspace come from config/env/flags; project-specific paths (folders, script
paths, variable paths) are supplied by the caller.

CONNECTIONS
  Configuration resolves as named connections. With no registry the sole
  connection is `default`, resolved by the cascade (first non-empty wins):
    1. flags          --url / --token / --workspace
    2. project env    .env.local then .env, walking up from $CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR (else cwd)
    3. user config    $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/windmill/credentials.env (default ~/.config/windmill/)
    4. process env    WINDMILL_URL / WINDMILL_API_TOKEN / WINDMILL_WORKSPACE
  Same WINDMILL_* keys at every tier; the project you're in wins, process env is
  the fallback (so a deployed host's injected env governs when no config file is
  present). Never pass the token on the command line.

  A project that talks to several Windmill instances declares them in
  <project>/.capabilities/windmill/connections.json:
    {
      "default": "<id>",
      "connections": {
        "<id>": {
          "url": "https://wm.example.com", "workspace": "main",
          "secret_env": "WINDMILL_<ID>_API_TOKEN",
          "allow_write": true
        }
      }
    }
  The registry resolves project envelope first, else the machine-level
  ~/.config/windmill/connections.json; first found wins, never merged.

  Only the token is secret: the entry names the env var holding it
  ("secret_env"); the value resolves through the cascade (project .env(.local)
  → user credentials.env → process env). "allow_write": false makes the
  connection read-only: every mutating verb (deploy, run, *-set, *-delete,
  *-ensure, *-create, provision) exits 4, and no flag lifts the gate.
  Writes default to allowed (a Windmill instance is the consumer's own).

  Selection: --connection <id> on every command. Unflagged, the registry's
  "default" pointer applies, else the sole entry; several entries without a
  pointer is refused as ambiguous. --workspace still switches workspaces
  within the selected connection's instance.

Acting as another user (isolation): the stored token is the workspace admin's.
  windmill --as <email> <cmd ...>             Run the call AS that workspace user, by
                                              minting a short-lived impersonation token
                                              from the admin token (nothing per-user is
                                              stored). Use it to execute under an operator
                                              identity so folder RBAC confines secret reads.

Commands:
  windmill help                               Print this document.
  windmill connections                        Where every connection's values resolve
                                              from (tier, source, secrets masked).
                                              Local only — no network.
  windmill doctor [--connection <id>]         Version + whoami + workspace reachability —
                                              every connection, or one.

  Scripts (Windmill versions by content hash; no PUT — update = archive+create):
  windmill scripts [--prefix f/x] [--limit N] List scripts (optionally by path prefix).
  windmill script-get <path>                  Show one script (incl. content, hash).
  windmill script-delete <path>               Hard-delete every version of a script at a
                                              path (irreversible; `deploy` recreates).
  windmill deploy <path> <file|->             Create/update a script from a file or
        [--lang bun] [--summary S]            stdin. Re-deploy archives the old hash
        [--description D] [--timeout 600]     then creates the new version at the same
        [--tag TAG]                           path. --tag pins a worker group/tag.

  Schedules (native Windmill cron — the schedule registry):
  windmill schedules [--limit N]              List schedules.
  windmill schedule-get <path>                Show one schedule.
  windmill schedule-set <path> --script SP    Create or update a cron schedule on a
        --cron "0 */5 * * * *"                script. Cron is Windmill format (6-7
        [--timezone Etc/UTC] [--arg k=v ...]  fields: sec min hour dom mon dow [year]).
        [--off]                               --arg sets static job args. --off creates
                                              it disabled.
  windmill schedule-enable <path> (--on|--off) Toggle a schedule.
  windmill schedule-delete <path>             Delete a schedule.

  Jobs / runs:
  windmill run <path> [--sync] [--arg k=v ...] Run a script. Async (default) returns the
        [--timeout N]                         job id; --sync blocks and returns result.
  windmill runs [--script PATH] [--limit N]   List recent runs (no logs/result body).
        [--running] [--success|--failed]
  windmill job <id>                           Show one job WITH result + logs.

  Variables (secrets + config):
  windmill vars [--prefix f/x]                List variables (names only; values hidden).
  windmill var-set <path> [--value V|--stdin] Create or update a variable. Defaults to
        [--plain] [--description D]           secret; --plain stores non-secret. Value
                                              from --value, --stdin, or a file path.
  windmill var-delete <path>                  Delete a variable.

  Folders:
  windmill folder-create <name> [--owner U]   Create a folder (e.g. myproj → f/myproj).
        [--owner U ...]                       --owner repeats; pass like u/alice or g/team.
  windmill folder-ensure <name> [--owner U]   Idempotent create-or-update of a folder's
                                              owners/ACL (owners also granted in extra_perms).

  HTTP triggers (custom routes that run a script/flow when called):
  windmill triggers [--limit N]               List HTTP triggers.
  windmill trigger-get <path>                 Show one trigger.
  windmill trigger-set <path> --script SP     Create or update an HTTP route on a script.
        --route inbound/webhook               --route is the URL path (no leading /). Returns
        [--method post] [--auth none]         the public URL. Idempotent (create-or-update).
        [--request-type sync] [--raw]         sync (default) returns the script's result, so a
        [--wrap-body] [--no-workspaced]       sync route can echo a handshake header; async
        [--flow] [--summary S]                returns a job id. auth=none is a public endpoint.
        [--description D] [--off]             --raw passes the body unparsed; --no-workspaced
                                              drops the workspace id from the URL; --off disables.
  windmill trigger-delete <path>              Delete a trigger.

  Users (workspace membership — the isolation identity):
  windmill users                              List workspace users (email, operator, admin).
  windmill user-ensure --email E [--operator] Idempotent: ensure a global user exists and is
        [--admin] [--name N]                  a member of this workspace. No token is minted
                                              or stored — act as the user via `--as E`.

  Data Tables (Postgres databases hosted inside the Windmill instance):
  windmill datatables                          List datatable stores in this workspace.
  windmill datatable run "<sql>" [--store S]   Execute SQL (DDL or DML) against a store.
        [--arg k=v ...] [--timeout N]         Runs as an ephemeral postgresql preview job
                                              with args.database = datatable://<store>.
                                              MUTATING — gated by allow_write.
  windmill datatable tables [--store S]        List tables in a store (default --store main).
  windmill datatable schema <table>            Column names + compact types for one table.
        [--store S] [--schema pub]            <table> may be "schema.table"; --schema
                                              (default public) applies when omitted.

  Instance databases (superadmin-only lifecycle of the underlying PG databases):
  windmill datatable-db list                   Statuses of every custom instance database.
  windmill datatable-db create <name>          Run CREATE DATABASE on the Windmill PG and
                                              grant custom_instance_user. MUTATING.
  windmill datatable-db drop <name>            Drop a custom instance database (irreversible).
                                              MUTATING. Superadmin token required — a
                                              non-superadmin surfaces as exit 2 with a hint.

  Provisioning (workspace skeleton — folder, operator user, scripts):
  windmill verify [--folder NS]               Read-only: check the workspace skeleton against
        [--operator E] [--scripts-dir D]      live state (folder+owners, operator user, each
        [<manifest.json>]                     discovered script) and report per-item ok + `ready`.
  windmill provision [--folder NS]            Idempotent, non-destructive apply of that skeleton.
        [--operator E] [--operator-name N]    Never deletes; never overwrites a present secret.
        [--owner U ...] [--scripts-dir D]     Inputs resolve from config unless flagged:
        [<manifest.json>]                       folder    --folder | WINDMILL_FOLDER (the namespace)
                                                operator  --operator | WINDMILL_OPERATOR (email) +
                                                          --operator-name | WINDMILL_OPERATOR_NAME
                                                owners    the operator user, plus any --owner
                                                scripts   *.ts under --scripts-dir (path
                                                          f/<folder>/<stem>; example_* skipped)
                                              Variables are NOT provisioned here: the box↔Windmill
                                              SSH vars are wired by the consumer's box routine. Pass
                                              an explicit <manifest.json> to override config-discovery
                                              (schema: {folder, owners[], users[], variables[],
                                              scripts[], schedules[]}; file paths relative to it).

References:
  <path> values are Windmill paths like f/myproj/runner (folder-scoped). The
  workspace is NOT part of the path — it comes from --workspace / WINDMILL_WORKSPACE.

I/O contract:
  - Success: JSON (or a bare string for scalar responses like a hash/job-id) on
    stdout, exit 0.
  - Error:   {"error": {"code","message","hint","status"}} on stderr, non-zero exit.

Contract commands (the same on every capability):
  windmill stub                                 One-line awareness text.
  windmill manifest --json                      Machine-readable declaration.
  windmill guide [<topic>]                      Guide topics / one guide body,
                                                 fetched live from the docs base.
  windmill ids list|get <l>|set <l> <v>|rm <l>  The project identifiers envelope
                [--note <text>]                  (.capabilities/windmill/identifiers.json).
  windmill refs                                 Menu of the project's reference
                                                 files for this capability.

Exit codes:
  0 success | 2 auth | 3 not found | 4 policy refusal (the project gate, or a
  write verb on a read-only connection — ask the user, never lift a gate
  yourself) | 5 server/network | 6 input/validation

Notes:
  - Worker model: a worker runs ONE job at a time for its whole duration; long jobs
    block a slot. Keep jobs bounded; use --tag to route heavy jobs to a dedicated
    worker group so they don't starve other scripts on a shared instance.
  - Timeout is YOURS to set: --timeout on deploy (default 600s) hard-kills any run that
    overruns. It is not a fixed platform limit — choose it per script to fit the job's
    real worst-case duration, and keep each job a bounded step rather than a long wait.
  - Lock resolves async after deploy: a freshly-deployed bun/deno script is not runnable
    until Windmill computes its dependency lock (seconds). Until then `run` returns
    404 "script not found at name" even though `scripts` lists it. `deploy` does not wait
    — poll `script-get <path>` until its `lock` field is non-null, then run.
  - Scalar endpoints (deploy hash, run job-id, version) return a bare string, not an
    object — that's expected.
"""

import argparse
import json
import os
import re
import secrets
import sys
import time
from datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone
from pathlib import Path
from typing import NoReturn

import httpx

TIMEOUT = httpx.Timeout(60.0)
MAX_RETRIES = 3

# --- Capability declaration (protocol 2) — one home for every contract fact --

NAME = "windmill"
PROTOCOL = 2
SUMMARY = ("Windmill CLI over the REST API — deploy scripts, attach cron "
           "schedules, run jobs, read run history/logs, and manage secret "
           "variables and folders.")
SCOPE = "project"   # credential scope: "project" | "user"
CRED_KEYS = [
    {"key": "WINDMILL_URL", "secret": False, "required": True,
     "note": "instance base URL"},
    {"key": "WINDMILL_API_TOKEN", "secret": True, "required": True,
     "note": "workspace admin API token"},
    {"key": "WINDMILL_WORKSPACE", "secret": False, "required": True,
     "note": "workspace id"},
    {"key": "WINDMILL_FOLDER", "secret": False, "required": False,
     "note": "default folder for deploys"},
]
WRITE_VERBS = {     # domain verbs that mutate the instance
    "deploy", "script-delete", "schedule-set", "schedule-enable",
    "schedule-delete", "run", "var-set", "var-delete", "folder-create",
    "folder-ensure", "trigger-set", "trigger-delete", "user-ensure",
    "provision",
    # sub-verb forms: `datatable run` executes DDL/DML; `datatable-db create/drop`
    # touch the instance's actual PG databases.
    "datatable:run", "datatable-db:create", "datatable-db:drop",
}
WRITE_DEFAULT = True    # writes stay inside an instance the consumer owns
DOCS_BASE = ("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ai-cluster-one/capabilities/"
             "main/capabilities/windmill/guides/")
TOPICS = ["data-tables", "operational", "provisioning", "scheduled-orchestration", "script-authoring"]
STATE = False       # True when the capability writes session/cache state
POST_INSTALL: list = []
_STATE_HOME = Path(os.environ.get("XDG_STATE_HOME") or (Path.home() / ".local" / "state"))

_CONFIG_HOME = Path(os.environ.get("XDG_CONFIG_HOME") or (Path.home() / ".config"))
CONFIG_DIR = _CONFIG_HOME / "windmill"
CREDENTIALS_ENV = CONFIG_DIR / "credentials.env"
CONN_KEYS = ("WINDMILL_URL", "WINDMILL_API_TOKEN", "WINDMILL_WORKSPACE")


# >>> contract: capability core (generated — edit contract/preamble.py, run `capabilities sync-contract`) >>>

# --- Error reporting ---------------------------------------------------------

def _die(exit_code: int, code: str, message: str,
         hint: str | None = None, status: int | None = None) -> NoReturn:
    err: dict = {"code": code, "message": message}
    if hint:
        err["hint"] = hint
    if status is not None:
        err["status"] = status
    sys.stderr.write(json.dumps({"error": err}, ensure_ascii=False) + "\n")
    sys.exit(exit_code)


def _emit(value) -> None:
    if isinstance(value, str):
        sys.stdout.write(value)
        if value and not value.endswith("\n"):
            sys.stdout.write("\n")
    else:
        sys.stdout.write(json.dumps(value, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2) + "\n")


# --- Project / file plumbing -------------------------------------------------

def _parse_env_file(path: Path) -> dict:
    """Parse a KEY=VALUE env/dotenv file. Missing/unreadable file -> {}."""
    out: dict = {}
    try:
        text = path.read_text()
    except OSError:
        return out
    for line in text.splitlines():
        line = line.strip()
        if not line or line.startswith("#") or "=" not in line:
            continue
        k, v = line.split("=", 1)
        k = k.strip()
        if k.startswith("export "):
            k = k[len("export "):].strip()
        out[k] = v.strip().strip('"').strip("'")
    return out


def _project_root() -> Path | None:
    """Nearest project root, walking up from $CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR (else cwd):
    the first directory holding .capabilities/, .env(.local), or .git.
    $HOME is never a project root (the machine registry lives there)."""
    start = os.environ.get("CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR") or os.getcwd()
    here = Path(start).resolve()
    home = Path.home().resolve()
    for d in (here, *here.parents):
        if d == home:
            return None
        if ((d / ".capabilities").is_dir() or (d / ".env").exists()
                or (d / ".env.local").exists() or (d / ".git").is_dir()):
            return d
    return None


def _project_env() -> dict:
    """Project .env(.local) at the project root. .env.local overrides .env."""
    root = _project_root()
    if root is None:
        return {}
    merged = _parse_env_file(root / ".env")
    merged.update(_parse_env_file(root / ".env.local"))  # .local wins
    return merged


def _gate() -> None:
    """absent → run; enabled → run; disabled → exit 4. Unreadable never blocks."""
    root = _project_root()
    if root is None:
        return
    gate_file = root / ".capabilities" / "settings.json"
    try:
        entry = json.loads(gate_file.read_text()).get("capabilities", {}).get(NAME)
    except (OSError, ValueError):
        return
    if isinstance(entry, dict) and entry.get("enabled") is False:
        _die(4, "disabled",
             f"{NAME} is disabled in this project ({gate_file})",
             "Do not enable it yourself — ask the user whether to enable it, then stop.")


def _env_dir() -> Path | None:
    """The capability's envelope dir in the project: .capabilities/<NAME>/."""
    root = _project_root()
    return (root / ".capabilities" / NAME) if root is not None else None


def _state_dir() -> Path:
    """State follows the scope of the credentials that minted it; project state
    lands inside the envelope only where .capabilities/ already exists."""
    if SCOPE == "project":
        root = _project_root()
        if root is not None and (root / ".capabilities").is_dir():
            return root / ".capabilities" / NAME / "state"
    return _STATE_HOME / NAME


# --- Capability contract (protocol 2) — the declaration surface --------------

def _docs_base() -> str:
    key = f"{NAME.upper()}_DOCS_BASE"
    return (_project_env().get(key)
            or _parse_env_file(CREDENTIALS_ENV).get(key)
            or os.environ.get(key)
            or DOCS_BASE)


def _cmd_guide(argv: list[str]) -> None:
    if not argv:
        _emit(sorted(TOPICS)); return
    topic = argv[0]
    if topic not in TOPICS:
        _die(3, "not_found", f"no guide topic {topic!r}",
             f"topics: {', '.join(sorted(TOPICS)) or 'none shipped'}")
    import urllib.error as _ue
    import urllib.request as _ur
    url = _docs_base().rstrip("/") + "/" + topic + ".md"
    cache_dir = _STATE_HOME / NAME / "guides"
    cache, etag_f = cache_dir / f"{topic}.md", cache_dir / f"{topic}.etag"
    headers = {}
    if cache.exists() and etag_f.exists():
        headers["If-None-Match"] = etag_f.read_text().strip()
    try:
        req = _ur.Request(url, headers=headers)
        with _ur.urlopen(req, timeout=10.0) as resp:
            text = resp.read().decode(resp.headers.get_content_charset() or "utf-8")
            cache_dir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
            cache.write_text(text)
            if resp.headers.get("etag"):
                etag_f.write_text(resp.headers["etag"])
            _emit(text); return
    except _ue.HTTPError as e:
        if e.code == 304 and cache.exists():
            _emit(cache.read_text()); return
        if e.code == 404:
            _die(3, "not_found", f"guide {topic!r} missing upstream", url)
        err = f"upstream returned {e.code}"
    except _ue.URLError as e:
        err = str(e.reason)
    except OSError as e:
        err = str(e)
    if cache.exists():
        sys.stderr.write(json.dumps(
            {"warning": f"upstream unreachable; serving cached copy ({err})"},
            ensure_ascii=False) + "\n")
        _emit(cache.read_text()); return
    _die(5, "network_error", f"could not fetch guide {topic!r}; no cache exists", url)


def _render_ids_markdown(data: dict) -> str:
    """Render the {label: {value, note}} envelope as the labelled markdown
    list the manager's `capabilities ids <NAME>` also produces — one shared
    format across the ids surface and the identifiers section of `help`."""
    lines: list[str] = []
    for label, entry in sorted(data.items()):
        entry = entry if isinstance(entry, dict) else {"value": entry}
        v = entry.get("value")
        vs = f"`{v}`" if isinstance(v, str) else "`" + json.dumps(v, ensure_ascii=False) + "`"
        line = f"- **{label}**: {vs}"
        note = entry.get("note")
        if note:
            line += f" — {note}"
        lines.append(line)
    return "\n".join(lines)


def _identifiers_section() -> str:
    """The Identifiers block appended to the bare top-level help — deterministic
    first-touch surfacing of `.capabilities/<NAME>/identifiers.json` so an
    agent following the `<NAME> help` startup protocol loads the discovered
    labels/values/notes into context at once. Empty when no project envelope
    or nothing recorded (do not bloat help with an empty section)."""
    envdir = _env_dir()
    if envdir is None:
        return ""
    ids_file = envdir / "identifiers.json"
    if not ids_file.exists():
        return ""
    try:
        data = json.loads(ids_file.read_text())
    except (OSError, ValueError):
        return ""
    if not isinstance(data, dict) or not data:
        return ""
    header = (
        "\n═══ Identifiers ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n\n"
        f"Structural lookups discovered for `{NAME}` in this project. Fetch a single\n"
        f"raw value with `{NAME} ids get <label>`; the full envelope is also at\n"
        f"`capabilities ids {NAME}`.\n\n"
    )
    return header + _render_ids_markdown(data) + "\n"


def _cmd_help() -> None:
    """Bare top-level help: the CLI's HELP body (module-level `HELP` if
    defined, else the module docstring), then the project's Identifiers
    section. Only fires when no extra args follow — per-verb help stays
    untouched so `<NAME> help <subcommand>` is not intercepted."""
    g = globals()
    text = g.get("HELP") or g.get("__doc__") or ""
    if text.startswith("\n"):
        text = text.lstrip("\n")
    sys.stdout.write(text)
    if text and not text.endswith("\n"):
        sys.stdout.write("\n")
    section = _identifiers_section()
    if section:
        sys.stdout.write(section)


def _cmd_ids(argv: list[str]) -> None:
    sub = argv[0] if argv else "list"
    envdir = _env_dir()
    ids_file = (envdir / "identifiers.json") if envdir else None
    data: dict = {}
    if ids_file and ids_file.exists():
        try:
            data = json.loads(ids_file.read_text())
        except ValueError:
            _die(6, "bad_envelope", f"{ids_file} is not valid JSON")
    if sub == "list":
        _emit(data); return
    if sub == "get":
        if len(argv) < 2 or argv[1] not in data:
            _die(3, "not_found", "unknown identifier label",
                 f"`{NAME} ids list` shows the labels")
        _emit((data[argv[1]] or {}).get("value")); return
    if sub == "set":
        if len(argv) < 3:
            _die(6, "input", f"usage: {NAME} ids set <label> <value> [--note <text>]")
        if envdir is None or not envdir.parent.is_dir():
            _die(6, "no_envelope", "no .capabilities/ envelope in this project",
                 "run `capabilities init` first")
        label, raw = argv[1], argv[2]
        try:
            value = json.loads(raw)
        except ValueError:
            value = raw
        note = ""
        if "--note" in argv:
            ni = argv.index("--note")
            if ni + 1 >= len(argv):
                _die(6, "input", "--note needs a value")
            note = argv[ni + 1]
        data[label] = {"value": value, "note": note or (data.get(label) or {}).get("note", "")}
        envdir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
        ids_file.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2, sort_keys=True) + "\n")
        _emit({"set": label}); return
    if sub == "rm":
        if len(argv) < 2 or argv[1] not in data:
            _die(3, "not_found", "unknown identifier label",
                 f"`{NAME} ids list` shows the labels")
        del data[argv[1]]
        ids_file.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2, sort_keys=True) + "\n")
        _emit({"removed": argv[1]}); return
    _die(6, "input", f"unknown ids subcommand {sub!r}", f"{NAME} ids list|get|set|rm")


def _cmd_refs() -> None:
    envdir = _env_dir()
    refdir = (envdir / "reference") if envdir else None
    out = []
    if refdir and refdir.is_dir():
        for md in sorted(refdir.glob("*.md")):
            name = desc = None
            try:
                lines = md.read_text().splitlines()
            except OSError:
                continue
            if lines and lines[0].strip() == "---":
                for line in lines[1:30]:
                    if line.strip() == "---":
                        break
                    if line.startswith("name:"):
                        name = line.split(":", 1)[1].strip()
                    elif line.startswith("description:"):
                        desc = line.split(":", 1)[1].strip()
            if name:
                out.append({"name": name, "description": desc or "", "path": str(md)})
    _emit(out)


def _contract(argv: list[str]) -> None:
    """Dispatch the contract verbs; domain verbs fall through to the CLI's own
    parser. Runs after _gate(), before any credential is resolved.

    `help` is a contract verb only when bare (no extra args) — the top-level
    dump plus the Identifiers section. `<NAME> help <subcommand>` falls
    through to the CLI so per-verb help stays clean."""
    cmd = argv[0] if argv else ""
    if cmd == "stub":
        _emit(f"{SUMMARY} Run `{NAME} help`.")
    elif cmd == "manifest":
        _emit({"name": NAME, "protocol": PROTOCOL, "summary": SUMMARY,
               "credentials": {"scope": SCOPE, "keys": CRED_KEYS},
               "docs": {"base": DOCS_BASE, "topics": sorted(TOPICS)},
               "state": STATE, "post_install": POST_INSTALL})
    elif cmd == "guide":
        _cmd_guide(argv[1:])
    elif cmd == "ids":
        _cmd_ids(argv[1:])
    elif cmd == "refs":
        _cmd_refs()
    elif cmd == "connections":
        _cmd_connections()
    elif cmd == "help" and len(argv) == 1:
        _cmd_help()
    else:
        return
    sys.exit(0)

# <<< contract: capability core <<<


# --- Config (cascade: flags > project .env > user config > process env) ------


# >>> contract: connections (generated — edit contract/preamble.py, run `capabilities sync-contract`) >>>

def _resolve_env_key(key: str) -> tuple[str | None, str | None, Path | None]:
    """Resolve one env key through cascade tiers 2-4: project .env(.local) →
    user credentials.env → process env. Returns (value, tier, source)."""
    root = _project_root()
    if root is not None:
        for fname in (".env.local", ".env"):
            val = _parse_env_file(root / fname).get(key)
            if val:
                return val, "project", root / fname
    val = _parse_env_file(CREDENTIALS_ENV).get(key)
    if val:
        return val, "user", CREDENTIALS_ENV
    val = os.environ.get(key)
    if val:
        return val, "env", None
    return None, None, None


def _mask(value: str) -> str:
    return ("…" + value[-4:]) if len(value) >= 8 else "****"


def _connections_registry() -> tuple[dict | None, Path | None]:
    """The connections envelope and its path: project envelope first, else the
    user config home. First found wins, never merged; (None, None) when neither
    declares one (the implicit default connection applies)."""
    envdir = _env_dir()
    candidates = ([envdir / "connections.json"] if envdir else []) + \
                 [_CONFIG_HOME / NAME / "connections.json"]
    for reg_file in candidates:
        if not reg_file.is_file():
            continue
        try:
            raw = json.loads(reg_file.read_text())
        except (ValueError, OSError) as e:
            _die(6, "bad_config", f"cannot read {reg_file}: {e}")
        if not isinstance(raw, dict) or not isinstance(raw.get("connections"), dict) \
                or not raw["connections"]:
            _die(6, "bad_config", f"{reg_file} is not a connections envelope",
                 'expected {"default": "<id>", "connections": { ... }}')
        return raw, reg_file
    return None, None


def _select_connection(reg: dict | None, wanted: str | None) -> tuple[str, dict | None]:
    """flag → default pointer → sole entry → die 6. No registry → the implicit
    default. A connection's own `address` field selects it too (used where a
    connection carries a human-recognizable address; absent fields never match)."""
    if reg is None:
        if wanted and wanted != "default":
            _die(6, "unknown_connection",
                 "no connections registry; the sole connection is 'default'",
                 "the implicit default resolves from the credential cascade")
        return "default", None
    conns = reg["connections"]
    if wanted:
        if wanted in conns:
            return wanted, conns[wanted]
        for cid, entry in conns.items():
            if (entry or {}).get("address", "").lower() == wanted.lower():
                return cid, entry
        _die(6, "unknown_connection", f"no connection matches {wanted!r}",
             f"known: {', '.join(conns)}")
    default = reg.get("default")
    if default:
        if default not in conns:
            _die(6, "bad_default", f"default points to unknown connection {default!r}",
                 f"known: {', '.join(conns)}")
        return default, conns[default]
    if len(conns) == 1:
        cid = next(iter(conns))
        return cid, conns[cid]
    _die(6, "ambiguous_connection",
         f"registry defines {len(conns)} connections and no default; "
         f"pass --connection <id>",
         f"known: {', '.join(conns)}")


def _write_gate(conn_id: str, allow_write: bool, verb: str) -> None:
    """Policy from the committed registry; nothing in the cascade lifts it."""
    if verb in WRITE_VERBS and not allow_write:
        _die(4, "read_only",
             f"connection {conn_id!r} does not allow writes",
             "Do not lift the gate yourself — ask the user; granting is "
             "`allow_write: true` on this connection in connections.json.")


def _key_report(key: str, secret: bool, required: bool,
                value: str | None, tier: str | None, source) -> dict:
    return {"key": key, "secret": secret, "required": required,
            "set": bool(value), "tier": tier if value else None,
            "source": str(source) if (value and source) else None,
            "value": (_mask(value) if secret else value) if value else None}


def _missing_required(keys: list) -> list:
    """Required report rows (from _key_report) that did not resolve through the
    cascade — empty ⇒ credentials present. The primitive behind doctor's
    network-free readiness gate, read from the same per-key resolution
    `connections` reports, so the gate and the report can never disagree."""
    return [k["key"] for k in keys if k["required"] and not k["set"]]


def _doctor_gate(report: dict, wanted: str | None) -> None:
    """doctor's network-free readiness gate. Refuse with exit 2 — naming the
    unresolved required keys, before any round-trip — when a connection under
    test cannot resolve its required config through the cascade, so readiness is
    judged by the same resolution `connections` reports, never a parallel check.
    Checks the selected connection, else every connection in the report."""
    conns = report.get("connections") or {}
    targets = [wanted] if (wanted and wanted in conns) else list(conns)
    problems: dict = {}
    for cid in targets:
        miss = _missing_required((conns.get(cid) or {}).get("keys") or [])
        if miss:
            problems[cid] = miss
    if problems:
        detail = "; ".join(f"{c}: {', '.join(ks)}" for c, ks in sorted(problems.items()))
        _die(2, "credentials_missing",
             f"unresolved required config — {detail}",
             f"set each in the project .env/.env.local, the user credentials.env, "
             f"or process env; `{NAME} connections` shows where every value resolves")

# <<< contract: connections <<<


def _build_conn(cid: str, entry: dict | None, args) -> tuple[dict | None, dict | None]:
    """Materialize one connection. Returns (conn, problem) — problem is an
    error dict ({"exit", "code", "message", "hint"?}) instead of a die, so
    doctor can report every connection rather than stopping at the first."""
    if entry is None:   # the implicit default — flat keys through the cascade
        url = getattr(args, "url", None) or _resolve_env_key("WINDMILL_URL")[0]
        token = (getattr(args, "token", None)
                 or _resolve_env_key("WINDMILL_API_TOKEN")[0])
        workspace = (getattr(args, "workspace", None)
                     or _resolve_env_key("WINDMILL_WORKSPACE")[0])
        if not url or not token:
            return None, {
                "exit": 2, "code": "missing_credentials",
                "message": "WINDMILL_URL and WINDMILL_API_TOKEN are required",
                "hint": f"set them in a project .env(.local), {CREDENTIALS_ENV}, "
                        f"the environment, or via --url/--token — or declare a "
                        f"connections registry (.capabilities/{NAME}/connections.json)"}
        if not workspace:
            return None, {
                "exit": 6, "code": "missing_workspace",
                "message": "WINDMILL_WORKSPACE is required",
                "hint": "set WINDMILL_WORKSPACE in a project .env, the user "
                        "config, the environment, or pass --workspace"}
        return {"id": cid, "allow_write": WRITE_DEFAULT, "url": url.rstrip("/"),
                "token": token, "workspace": workspace,
                "script_timeout_default": None, "script_timeout_min": None}, None
    url = getattr(args, "url", None) or entry.get("url")
    workspace = getattr(args, "workspace", None) or entry.get("workspace")
    secret_env = entry.get("secret_env")
    if not secret_env:
        return None, {"exit": 6, "code": "no_secret_env",
                      "message": f"connection {cid!r} is missing 'secret_env'"}
    token = _resolve_env_key(secret_env)[0]
    if not token:
        return None, {
            "exit": 2, "code": "missing_secret",
            "message": f"env var {secret_env} (for connection {cid!r}) is unset",
            "hint": f"set {secret_env} in the project's .env / .env.local, "
                    f"{CREDENTIALS_ENV}, or the environment"}
    missing = [k for k, v in {"url": url, "workspace": workspace}.items() if not v]
    if missing:
        return None, {"exit": 6, "code": "incomplete_connection",
                      "message": f"connection {cid!r} missing: {', '.join(missing)}"}
    return {"id": cid, "allow_write": bool(entry.get("allow_write", WRITE_DEFAULT)),
            "url": url.rstrip("/"), "token": token, "workspace": workspace,
            "script_timeout_default": entry.get("script_timeout_default"),
            "script_timeout_min": entry.get("script_timeout_min")}, None


def _resolve_conn(args) -> dict:
    reg, _ = _connections_registry()
    cid, entry = _select_connection(reg, getattr(args, "connection", None))
    conn, problem = _build_conn(cid, entry, args)
    if problem:
        _die(problem["exit"], problem["code"], problem["message"],
             problem.get("hint"))
    return conn


def _resolve_deploy_timeout(flag: int | None, conn: dict) -> int:
    """Pick the deploy timeout — explicit flag, else the connection's
    script_timeout_default, else 600 — then enforce script_timeout_min as a
    hard floor. An explicit flag below the floor refuses the deploy."""
    floor = conn.get("script_timeout_min")
    if flag is not None:
        if floor is not None and flag < floor:
            _die(6, "timeout_below_floor",
                 f"--timeout {flag} is below the connection floor "
                 f"script_timeout_min={floor}",
                 f"raise --timeout to at least {floor} or relax the "
                 f"connection's script_timeout_min")
        return flag
    resolved = conn.get("script_timeout_default") or 600
    if floor is not None and resolved < floor:
        resolved = floor
    return resolved


def _connections_report() -> dict:
    """The resolution report — every connection, every value, its winning tier
    and source, secrets masked. Local only: no network, no login attempt."""
    reg, reg_path = _connections_registry()
    report: dict = {"default": None, "connections": {}}
    if reg is None:
        keys = []
        for k in CRED_KEYS:
            value, tier, source = _resolve_env_key(k["key"])
            keys.append(_key_report(k["key"], k["secret"], k["required"],
                                    value, tier, source))
        report["default"] = "default"
        report["connections"]["default"] = {"allow_write": WRITE_DEFAULT, "keys": keys}
        return report
    conns = reg["connections"]
    report["default"] = reg.get("default") or \
        (next(iter(conns)) if len(conns) == 1 else None)
    for cid, entry in conns.items():
        entry = entry if isinstance(entry, dict) else {}
        keys = []
        for field, required in (("url", True), ("workspace", True), ("folder", False),
                                ("script_timeout_default", False),
                                ("script_timeout_min", False)):
            value = entry.get(field)
            keys.append(_key_report(field, False, required,
                                    str(value) if value is not None else None,
                                    "connection", reg_path))
        secret_env = entry.get("secret_env")
        if secret_env:
            value, tier, source = _resolve_env_key(secret_env)
            keys.append(_key_report(secret_env, True, True, value, tier, source))
        else:
            keys.append(_key_report("secret_env", False, True, None, None, None))
        report["connections"][cid] = {
            "allow_write": bool(entry.get("allow_write", WRITE_DEFAULT)),
            "keys": keys}
    return report


def _cmd_connections() -> None:
    _emit(_connections_report())


# --- HTTP --------------------------------------------------------------------

def _impersonate(url: str, admin_token: str, ws: str, email: str) -> str:
    """Mint a short-lived (15-min) token that acts as `email`, via the super-admin
    token. Per-user tokens are never stored — this is the on-demand alternative."""
    exp = (datetime.now(timezone.utc) + timedelta(minutes=15)).strftime("%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ")
    with _client(url, admin_token) as c:
        return _request(c, "POST", "/api/users/tokens/impersonate",
                        json_body={"impersonate_email": email, "label": "windmill-cli",
                                   "workspace_id": ws, "expiration": exp}, raw=True)


def _client(url: str, token: str) -> httpx.Client:
    return httpx.Client(
        base_url=url,
        timeout=TIMEOUT,
        headers={
            "Authorization": f"Bearer {token}",
            "Accept": "application/json",
            "Content-Type": "application/json",
        },
    )


def _is_err(value) -> bool:
    """True if `value` is the soft-error marker returned by _request(soft=True)."""
    return isinstance(value, dict) and "__http_error__" in value


def _request(client: httpx.Client, method: str, path: str,
             params: dict | None = None, json_body: dict | None = None,
             raw: bool = False, soft: bool = False):
    """Return parsed JSON, or — for bare scalar/text endpoints — the trimmed text.

    Windmill returns bare quoted scalars (hashes, job ids) which json() decodes to
    a str; /api/version returns unquoted text. raw=True forces text handling.

    soft=True: on a 4xx, return {"__http_error__": status, "message": ...} instead of
    exiting — for idempotent existence checks that expect a miss (test with _is_err).
    """
    last_status: int | None = None
    for attempt in range(1, MAX_RETRIES + 1):
        try:
            resp = client.request(method, path, params=params, json=json_body)
        except httpx.TimeoutException:
            if attempt < MAX_RETRIES:
                time.sleep(attempt * 1.5)
                continue
            _die(5, "timeout", f"request timed out: {method} {path}",
                 "Windmill was unresponsive")
        except httpx.RequestError as e:
            _die(5, "network_error", f"network error: {e}", "check WINDMILL_URL / connectivity")

        last_status = resp.status_code
        if resp.status_code == 429:
            retry_after = float(resp.headers.get("Retry-After", "1"))
            if attempt < MAX_RETRIES:
                time.sleep(retry_after)
                continue
            _die(5, "rate_limited", "rate-limited", status=429)
        if resp.status_code >= 500:
            if attempt < MAX_RETRIES:
                time.sleep(attempt * 1.5)
                continue
            _die(5, "server_error", f"Windmill returned {resp.status_code}",
                 (resp.text or "")[:300], status=resp.status_code)

        if resp.status_code >= 400:
            body = (resp.text or "").strip()
            msg = body[:400] or "unknown error"
            try:
                j = resp.json()
                if isinstance(j, dict):
                    msg = j.get("error", {}).get("message") if isinstance(j.get("error"), dict) else None
                    msg = msg or j.get("error") or j.get("message") or body[:400]
            except ValueError:
                pass
            if soft:
                return {"__http_error__": resp.status_code, "message": msg}
            if resp.status_code in (401, 403):
                _die(2, "unauthorized", msg, "token invalid or lacks workspace access",
                     status=resp.status_code)
            if resp.status_code == 404:
                _die(3, "not_found", msg, "verify the path and workspace",
                     status=resp.status_code)
            if resp.status_code in (400, 409, 422):
                _die(6, "invalid_request", msg, status=resp.status_code)
            _die(5, "api_error", msg, status=resp.status_code)

        text = resp.text
        if raw:
            return text.strip().strip('"')
        try:
            # strict=False: Windmill job logs carry raw ANSI control bytes that
            # strict JSON rejects — parse leniently so `job`/`runs` stay usable.
            return json.loads(text, strict=False)
        except ValueError:
            return text.strip().strip('"')

    _die(5, "exhausted_retries", f"exhausted {MAX_RETRIES} attempts on {method} {path}",
         status=last_status)


# --- Output ------------------------------------------------------------------

def _read_text(src: str | None) -> str:
    if src is None or src == "-":
        return sys.stdin.read()
    p = Path(src)
    if p.exists():
        return p.read_text()
    return src


def _parse_args_kv(pairs: list[str]) -> dict:
    out: dict = {}
    for kv in pairs:
        if "=" not in kv:
            _die(6, "bad_arg", f"--arg expects key=value, got {kv!r}")
        k, v = kv.split("=", 1)
        # best-effort typing: JSON value if it parses, else string
        try:
            out[k] = json.loads(v)
        except ValueError:
            out[k] = v
    return out


def W(ws: str, suffix: str) -> str:
    return f"/api/w/{ws}/{suffix}"


# --- Commands ----------------------------------------------------------------

def _check_connection(conn: dict) -> dict:
    """One connection's round-trip, reported rather than died — doctor covers
    every connection, so a broken one becomes a finding, not a stop."""
    out: dict = {"url": conn["url"], "workspace": conn["workspace"]}
    try:
        with _client(conn["url"], conn["token"]) as c:
            r = c.get("/api/version")
            if r.status_code >= 400:
                cat = 2 if r.status_code in (401, 403) else 5
                return out | {"ok": False, "category": cat,
                              "error": f"/api/version returned {r.status_code}"}
            out["version"] = r.text.strip()
            r = c.get(f"/api/w/{conn['workspace']}/users/whoami")
            if r.status_code >= 400:
                cat = 2 if r.status_code in (401, 403) else 5
                return out | {"ok": False, "category": cat,
                              "error": f"whoami returned {r.status_code}"}
            who = r.json()
            out["whoami"] = (who.get("username") or who.get("email")
                             if isinstance(who, dict) else who)
            r = c.get(f"/api/w/{conn['workspace']}/scripts/list",
                      params={"per_page": 1})
            out["scripts_reachable"] = r.status_code < 400
    except httpx.RequestError as e:
        return out | {"ok": False, "category": 5, "error": f"network error: {e}"}
    except ValueError as e:
        return out | {"ok": False, "category": 5, "error": f"bad response: {e}"}
    return out | {"ok": True}


def cmd_doctor(args) -> None:
    """Every connection bare; one with --connection. Exit 0 only when every
    examined connection is healthy, else the first failure's category."""
    _doctor_gate(_connections_report(), getattr(args, "connection", None))
    reg, _ = _connections_registry()
    if args.connection is not None or reg is None:
        targets = [_select_connection(reg, args.connection)]
    else:
        targets = list(reg["connections"].items())
    connections: dict = {}
    fail_exit = 0
    for cid, entry in targets:
        conn, problem = _build_conn(cid, entry, args)
        if problem:
            res = {"ok": False, "category": problem["exit"],
                   "error": problem["message"]}
            if problem.get("hint"):
                res["hint"] = problem["hint"]
        else:
            res = _check_connection(conn)
        if not res.get("ok") and not fail_exit:
            fail_exit = res.get("category") or 5
        res.pop("category", None)
        connections[cid] = res
    _emit({"ok": fail_exit == 0, "connections": connections})
    if fail_exit:
        sys.exit(fail_exit)


def cmd_scripts(c, ws, prefix, limit):
    params = {"per_page": limit}
    if prefix:
        params["path_start"] = prefix
    return _request(c, "GET", W(ws, "scripts/list"), params=params)


def cmd_script_get(c, ws, path):
    return _request(c, "GET", W(ws, f"scripts/get/p/{path}"))


def cmd_deploy(c, ws, path, content, lang, summary, description, timeout, tag):
    # Update = archive-then-create (no PUT). Carry forward prior metadata if present.
    prior_hash = None
    prior = _request(c, "GET", W(ws, f"scripts/get/p/{path}"), soft=True)
    if isinstance(prior, dict) and not _is_err(prior):
        prior_hash = prior.get("hash")
        lang = lang or prior.get("language")
        summary = summary if summary is not None else prior.get("summary")
        description = description if description is not None else prior.get("description")
    if prior_hash:
        _request(c, "POST", W(ws, f"scripts/archive/h/{prior_hash}"), raw=True)
    body = {
        "path": path,
        "content": content,
        "language": lang or "bun",
        "summary": summary or "",
        "description": description or "",
        "timeout": timeout,
    }
    if prior_hash:
        body["parent_hash"] = prior_hash
    if tag:
        body["tag"] = tag
    new_hash = _request(c, "POST", W(ws, "scripts/create"), json_body=body, raw=True)
    return {"path": path, "hash": new_hash, "language": body["language"],
            "archived": prior_hash, "tag": tag}


def cmd_script_delete(c, ws, path):
    """Hard-delete every version of a script at a path. Irreversible — there is no
    archive-then-restore here; use `deploy` to recreate if needed."""
    _request(c, "POST", W(ws, f"scripts/delete/p/{path}"), raw=True)
    return {"path": path, "deleted": True}


def cmd_schedules(c, ws, limit):
    return _request(c, "GET", W(ws, "schedules/list"), params={"per_page": limit})


def cmd_schedule_get(c, ws, path):
    return _request(c, "GET", W(ws, f"schedules/get/{path}"))


def cmd_schedule_set(c, ws, path, script, cron, timezone, args_kv, off):
    args = _parse_args_kv(args_kv)
    exists = not _is_err(_request(c, "GET", W(ws, f"schedules/get/{path}"), soft=True))
    if exists:
        body = {"schedule": cron, "timezone": timezone, "args": args,
                "script_path": script, "is_flow": False}
        _request(c, "POST", W(ws, f"schedules/update/{path}"), json_body=body)
        # enabled state is managed separately on update
        _request(c, "POST", W(ws, f"schedules/setenabled/{path}"),
                 json_body={"enabled": not off})
        return {"path": path, "updated": True, "enabled": not off, "cron": cron}
    body = {"path": path, "schedule": cron, "timezone": timezone, "args": args,
            "script_path": script, "is_flow": False, "enabled": not off}
    _request(c, "POST", W(ws, "schedules/create"), json_body=body)
    return {"path": path, "created": True, "enabled": not off, "cron": cron,
            "script_path": script}


def cmd_schedule_enable(c, ws, path, on):
    _request(c, "POST", W(ws, f"schedules/setenabled/{path}"), json_body={"enabled": on})
    return {"path": path, "enabled": on}


def cmd_schedule_delete(c, ws, path):
    _request(c, "DELETE", W(ws, f"schedules/delete/{path}"), raw=True)
    return {"path": path, "deleted": True}


def cmd_run(c, ws, path, sync, args_kv, timeout):
    args = _parse_args_kv(args_kv)
    params = {}
    if timeout:
        params["timeout"] = timeout
    if sync:
        result = _request(c, "POST", W(ws, f"jobs/run_wait_result/p/{path}"),
                          params=params, json_body=args)
        return {"path": path, "result": result}
    job_id = _request(c, "POST", W(ws, f"jobs/run/p/{path}"),
                      params=params, json_body=args, raw=True)
    return {"path": path, "job_id": job_id}


def cmd_runs(c, ws, script, limit, running, success, failed):
    params = {"per_page": limit, "no_logs": "true"}
    if script:
        params["script_path_exact"] = script
    if running:
        params["running"] = "true"
    if success:
        params["success"] = "true"
    if failed:
        params["success"] = "false"
    return _request(c, "GET", W(ws, "jobs/list"), params=params)


def cmd_job(c, ws, job_id):
    return _request(c, "GET", W(ws, f"jobs_u/get/{job_id}"))


def cmd_vars(c, ws, prefix):
    params = {}
    if prefix:
        params["path_start"] = prefix
    return _request(c, "GET", W(ws, "variables/list"), params=params)


def cmd_var_set(c, ws, path, value, secret, description):
    # create, fall back to update if it already exists
    r = _request(c, "POST", W(ws, "variables/create"),
                 json_body={"path": path, "value": value,
                            "is_secret": secret, "description": description or ""},
                 raw=True, soft=True)
    if not _is_err(r):
        return {"path": path, "created": True, "is_secret": secret}
    _request(c, "POST", W(ws, f"variables/update/{path}"),
             json_body={"value": value})
    return {"path": path, "updated": True, "is_secret": secret}


def cmd_var_delete(c, ws, path):
    _request(c, "DELETE", W(ws, f"variables/delete/{path}"), raw=True)
    return {"path": path, "deleted": True}


def cmd_folder_create(c, ws, name, owners):
    body = {"name": name, "owners": owners or [], "extra_perms": {}}
    _request(c, "POST", W(ws, "folders/create"), json_body=body, raw=True)
    return {"folder": f"f/{name}", "owners": owners or []}


def cmd_folder_ensure(c, ws, name, owners):
    """Idempotent: create the folder if absent, else update its owners/ACL.
    Owners are also granted in extra_perms so they retain read+write."""
    owners = owners or []
    extra = {o: True for o in owners}
    r = _request(c, "POST", W(ws, "folders/create"),
                 json_body={"name": name, "owners": owners, "extra_perms": extra},
                 raw=True, soft=True)
    if not _is_err(r):
        return {"folder": f"f/{name}", "owners": owners, "created": True}
    _request(c, "POST", W(ws, f"folders/update/{name}"),
             json_body={"owners": owners, "extra_perms": extra}, raw=True)
    return {"folder": f"f/{name}", "owners": owners, "updated": True}


# --- Data Tables (Postgres databases hosted inside the Windmill instance) ----

def cmd_datatables(c, ws):
    """List datatable stores in the workspace."""
    return _request(c, "GET", W(ws, "workspaces/list_datatables"))


def cmd_datatable_run(c, ws, sql, store, args_kv, timeout):
    """Execute SQL against a datatable store via an ephemeral postgresql preview.
    The preview body sets args.database = datatable://<store>; extra --arg values
    become additional preview args (e.g. named parameters for the SQL)."""
    args = _parse_args_kv(args_kv)
    args["database"] = f"datatable://{store}"
    params = {}
    if timeout:
        params["timeout"] = timeout
    body = {"language": "postgresql", "content": sql, "args": args}
    return _request(c, "POST", W(ws, "jobs/run_wait_result/preview"),
                    params=params, json_body=body)


def cmd_datatable_tables(c, ws, store):
    """List tables in one store. list_datatable_tables returns one entry per
    connected store; we filter to the requested one and surface its schemas map."""
    entries = _request(c, "GET", W(ws, "workspaces/list_datatable_tables")) or []
    for e in entries:
        if e.get("datatable_name") == store:
            if e.get("error"):
                _die(5, "datatable_error",
                     f"store {store!r} reported error: {e['error']}",
                     status=None)
            return {"store": store, "schemas": e.get("schemas") or {}}
    known = [e.get("datatable_name") for e in entries]
    _die(3, "not_found", f"no datatable store named {store!r} in this workspace",
         f"known: {', '.join(x for x in known if x) or 'none'}")


def cmd_datatable_schema(c, ws, table, store, schema):
    """Column names/types for one table. <table> may be 'schema.table' — an
    explicit --schema wins if given, else the segment before the dot, else
    the default 'public'."""
    if "." in table and schema is None:
        schema, table = table.split(".", 1)
    schema = schema or "public"
    params = {"datatable_name": store, "schema_name": schema, "table_name": table}
    return _request(c, "GET", W(ws, "workspaces/get_datatable_table_schema"),
                    params=params)


# --- Instance databases (superadmin-only lifecycle of the underlying PG dbs) --

def _datatable_db_call(c, method: str, path: str, json_body=None):
    """Wrapper for /settings endpoints — a non-superadmin token gets 401/403;
    surface it as exit 2 with a superadmin hint rather than the generic auth die."""
    r = _request(c, method, path, json_body=json_body, soft=True)
    if _is_err(r):
        st = r["__http_error__"]
        if st in (401, 403):
            _die(2, "not_superadmin", r.get("message") or "superadmin required",
                 "instance-database lifecycle requires a superadmin token; "
                 "use a superadmin's API token for this connection", status=st)
        _die(5, "api_error", r.get("message") or "settings endpoint failed", status=st)
    return r


def cmd_datatable_db_list(c):
    return _datatable_db_call(c, "POST", "/api/settings/list_custom_instance_pg_databases")


def cmd_datatable_db_create(c, name):
    r = _datatable_db_call(c, "POST",
                           f"/api/settings/setup_custom_instance_pg_database/{name}",
                           json_body={})
    return {"name": name, "created": True, "status": r}


def cmd_datatable_db_drop(c, name):
    _datatable_db_call(c, "POST",
                       f"/api/settings/drop_custom_instance_pg_database/{name}")
    return {"name": name, "dropped": True}


# --- HTTP triggers (custom routes that run a script/flow on request) ----------

def _route_url(url: str, ws: str, route_path: str, workspaced: bool) -> str:
    """The public URL a caller hits. Workspaced routes carry the workspace id."""
    rp = route_path.lstrip("/")
    return f"{url}/api/r/{ws}/{rp}" if workspaced else f"{url}/api/r/{rp}"


def cmd_triggers(c, ws, limit):
    return _request(c, "GET", W(ws, "http_triggers/list"), params={"per_page": limit})


def cmd_trigger_get(c, ws, path):
    return _request(c, "GET", W(ws, f"http_triggers/get/{path}"))


def cmd_trigger_set(c, ws, url, path, script, route, method, auth, request_type,
                    raw_string, wrap_body, workspaced, is_flow, summary, description, off):
    """Idempotent create-or-update of an HTTP route that runs a script/flow.

    `route` is the URL path (no leading /). `request_type` sync makes the response
    carry the script's return value (needed for handshake/echo webhooks); async
    returns a job id immediately. auth=none is a public endpoint."""
    route = route.lstrip("/")
    body = {
        "path": path,
        "script_path": script,
        "route_path": route,
        "is_flow": is_flow,
        "http_method": method,
        "authentication_method": auth,
        "request_type": request_type,
        "is_static_website": False,
        "workspaced_route": workspaced,
        "wrap_body": wrap_body,
        "raw_string": raw_string,
    }
    if summary is not None:
        body["summary"] = summary
    if description is not None:
        body["description"] = description
    if off:
        body["mode"] = "disabled"
    exists = not _is_err(_request(c, "GET", W(ws, f"http_triggers/get/{path}"), soft=True))
    public = _route_url(url, ws, route, workspaced)
    if exists:
        _request(c, "POST", W(ws, f"http_triggers/update/{path}"), json_body=body, raw=True)
        return {"path": path, "updated": True, "route": public, "method": method,
                "request_type": request_type, "auth": auth}
    _request(c, "POST", W(ws, "http_triggers/create"), json_body=body, raw=True)
    return {"path": path, "created": True, "route": public, "method": method,
            "request_type": request_type, "auth": auth}


def cmd_trigger_delete(c, ws, path):
    _request(c, "DELETE", W(ws, f"http_triggers/delete/{path}"), raw=True)
    return {"path": path, "deleted": True}


# --- Users (workspace membership + the isolation identity) -------------------

def _username_for(email: str) -> str:
    """Mirror Windmill's username derivation: local part, non-alphanumerics stripped."""
    return re.sub(r"[^a-z0-9]", "", email.split("@")[0].lower())


def cmd_users(c, ws):
    return _request(c, "GET", W(ws, "users/list"))


def cmd_user_ensure(c, ws, email, operator, is_admin, name):
    """Idempotent: ensure a global user exists and is a member of this workspace.
    Tolerates re-runs — 'already exists' / 'already in workspace' are no-ops.
    The user's token is NOT minted or stored: act as this user on demand with
    the global `--as <email>` flag, which impersonates via the admin token."""
    username = _username_for(email)
    created = not _is_err(_request(c, "POST", "/api/users/create",
                          json_body={"email": email, "password": secrets.token_hex(16),
                                     "super_admin": False, "name": name or "",
                                     "skip_email": True}, raw=True, soft=True))
    added = not _is_err(_request(c, "POST", W(ws, "workspaces/add_user"),
                        json_body={"email": email, "is_admin": is_admin, "operator": operator},
                        raw=True, soft=True))
    return {"email": email, "username": username, "operator": operator,
            "is_admin": is_admin, "created": created, "added_to_workspace": added}


# --- Manifest-driven provision / verify (declarative completeness) -----------

def _load_manifest(path: str) -> tuple[dict, Path]:
    p = Path(path).resolve()
    try:
        data = json.loads(p.read_text())
    except OSError as e:
        _die(6, "manifest_unreadable", f"cannot read manifest {path}: {e}")
    except ValueError as e:
        _die(6, "manifest_invalid", f"manifest {path} is not valid JSON: {e}")
    return data, p.parent


def _config_value(args, flag: str, env_key: str) -> str | None:
    """Resolve a non-secret provisioning scalar: flag > project .env(.local) > user
    config > process env. Mirrors the credential cascade for config-driven provision."""
    return (getattr(args, flag, None)
            or _project_env().get(env_key)
            or _parse_env_file(CREDENTIALS_ENV).get(env_key)
            or os.environ.get(env_key))


_EXT_LANG = {".ts": "bun", ".py": "python3", ".sh": "bash", ".go": "go"}


def _discover_scripts(scripts_dir: Path, folder: str) -> list[dict]:
    """Each deployable source under scripts_dir → a manifest script spec. Deploy path
    is f/<folder>/<stem>; lang from the extension; summary from a leading comment line.
    `example_*` files are templates, not deployables — skipped."""
    specs: list[dict] = []
    if not scripts_dir.is_dir():
        return specs
    for f in sorted(scripts_dir.iterdir()):
        if not f.is_file() or f.suffix not in _EXT_LANG or f.stem.startswith("example_"):
            continue
        summary = None
        for line in f.read_text().splitlines():
            s = line.strip()
            if s.startswith("#!"):
                continue  # shebang — keep scanning for a real comment
            if s.startswith("//"):
                summary = s.lstrip("/ ").strip(); break
            if s.startswith("#"):
                summary = s.lstrip("# ").strip(); break
            if s:
                break
        specs.append({"path": f"f/{folder}/{f.stem}", "file": f.name,
                      "lang": _EXT_LANG[f.suffix], "summary": summary})
    return specs


def _config_manifest(args) -> tuple[dict, Path]:
    """Build the workspace-skeleton manifest from config + flags + script discovery —
    the file-less default for provision/verify. Variables and schedules are out of
    scope here: the SSH var trio is the consumer's box-wiring routine's job, and a cron
    is an operational toggle attached with `schedule-set` when a source is wired."""
    folder = _config_value(args, "folder", "WINDMILL_FOLDER")
    if not folder:
        _die(6, "missing_folder", "no folder/namespace resolved",
             "pass --folder <ns> or set WINDMILL_FOLDER in the project .env")
    operator = _config_value(args, "operator", "WINDMILL_OPERATOR")
    if not operator:
        _die(6, "missing_config", "no operator user resolved",
             "set WINDMILL_OPERATOR (email) in config, or pass --operator")
    op_name = _config_value(args, "operator_name", "WINDMILL_OPERATOR_NAME")
    owners = list(dict.fromkeys([f"u/{operator.split('@')[0]}", *args.owner]))
    scripts_dir = Path(args.scripts_dir).resolve() if args.scripts_dir else None
    m = {
        "folder": folder,
        "owners": owners,
        "users": [{"email": operator, "operator": True, "name": op_name}],
        "variables": [],
        "scripts": _discover_scripts(scripts_dir, folder) if scripts_dir else [],
        "schedules": [],
    }
    return m, (scripts_dir or Path.cwd())


def _var_value(spec: dict) -> str | None:
    """Resolve a manifest variable's value: literal `value`, or `value_env`
    looked up in the project .env then the process env. None if neither/external."""
    if "value" in spec:
        return str(spec["value"])
    env_key = spec.get("value_env")
    if env_key:
        return _project_env().get(env_key) or os.environ.get(env_key)
    return None


def _check_manifest(c, ws, m: dict, base: Path) -> dict:
    """Read-only: compare the manifest to live state. Returns checks + overall ready."""
    checks: list[dict] = []

    folder = m.get("folder")
    owners = m.get("owners", [])
    if folder:
        f = _request(c, "GET", W(ws, f"folders/get/{folder}"), soft=True)
        if _is_err(f):
            checks.append({"item": f"folder f/{folder}", "ok": False, "detail": "absent"})
        else:
            have = set(f.get("owners") or [])
            ok = set(owners).issubset(have)
            checks.append({"item": f"folder f/{folder}", "ok": ok,
                           "detail": f"owners={sorted(have)}" if ok else f"missing owners {sorted(set(owners)-have)}"})

    members = {u.get("email"): u for u in (_request(c, "GET", W(ws, "users/list")) or [])}
    for u in m.get("users", []):
        em = u.get("email")
        cur = members.get(em)
        if not cur:
            checks.append({"item": f"user {em}", "ok": False, "detail": "not a workspace member"})
        else:
            ok = bool(cur.get("operator")) == bool(u.get("operator", False))
            checks.append({"item": f"user {em}", "ok": ok,
                           "detail": f"operator={cur.get('operator')}"})

    live_vars = {v["path"]: v for v in (_request(c, "GET", W(ws, "variables/list"),
                                                  params={"path_start": f"f/{folder}"} if folder else None) or [])}
    for v in m.get("variables", []):
        path = v["path"]
        cur = live_vars.get(path)
        tag = " (external)" if v.get("external") else ""
        if not cur:
            checks.append({"item": f"var {path}{tag}", "ok": False, "detail": "absent"})
        else:
            ok = bool(cur.get("is_secret")) == bool(v.get("secret", False))
            checks.append({"item": f"var {path}{tag}", "ok": ok,
                           "detail": f"secret={cur.get('is_secret')}"})

    for s in m.get("scripts", []):
        path = s["path"]
        sc = _request(c, "GET", W(ws, f"scripts/get/p/{path}"), soft=True)
        if _is_err(sc):
            checks.append({"item": f"script {path}", "ok": False, "detail": "absent"})
        else:
            locked = sc.get("lock") is not None
            errs = sc.get("has_deploy_errors")
            ok = locked and not errs
            checks.append({"item": f"script {path}", "ok": ok,
                           "detail": "ready" if ok else f"lock={'set' if locked else 'pending'} deploy_errors={errs}"})

    for sch in m.get("schedules", []):
        path = sch["path"]
        cur = _request(c, "GET", W(ws, f"schedules/get/{path}"), soft=True)
        if _is_err(cur):
            checks.append({"item": f"schedule {path}", "ok": False, "detail": "absent"})
        else:
            want = bool(sch.get("enabled", False))
            ok = bool(cur.get("enabled")) == want
            checks.append({"item": f"schedule {path}", "ok": ok,
                           "detail": f"enabled={cur.get('enabled')} (want {want})"})

    return {"ready": all(ch["ok"] for ch in checks), "checks": checks}


def cmd_verify(c, ws, m, base):
    return _check_manifest(c, ws, m, base)


def cmd_provision(c, ws, m, base, url, admin_token, conn):
    """Idempotent, non-destructive apply of the manifest. Never deletes; never
    overwrites a secret that is already present; `external` vars are reported,
    not minted (the project routine that owns the box mints those)."""
    actions: list[dict] = []

    folder = m.get("folder")
    if folder:
        actions.append(cmd_folder_ensure(c, ws, folder, m.get("owners", [])))

    for u in m.get("users", []):
        actions.append(cmd_user_ensure(c, ws, u["email"], bool(u.get("operator", False)),
                                        bool(u.get("admin", False)), u.get("name")))

    live_vars = {v["path"]: v for v in (_request(c, "GET", W(ws, "variables/list"),
                                                  params={"path_start": f"f/{folder}"} if folder else None) or [])}
    for v in m.get("variables", []):
        path = v["path"]
        if v.get("external"):
            actions.append({"var": path, "external": True,
                            "present": path in live_vars,
                            "note": v.get("note", "provisioned out-of-band")})
            continue
        if v.get("secret") and path in live_vars:
            actions.append({"var": path, "skipped": "secret already present"})
            continue
        value = _var_value(v)
        if value is None:
            actions.append({"var": path, "skipped": "no value resolved (value/value_env)"})
            continue
        actions.append(cmd_var_set(c, ws, path, value, bool(v.get("secret", False)),
                                   v.get("description")))

    for s in m.get("scripts", []):
        path, src = s["path"], (base / s["file"])
        content = src.read_text()
        cur = _request(c, "GET", W(ws, f"scripts/get/p/{path}"), soft=True)
        if isinstance(cur, dict) and not _is_err(cur) and (cur.get("content") or "").strip() == content.strip():
            actions.append({"script": path, "skipped": "unchanged"})
            continue
        timeout = _resolve_deploy_timeout(s.get("timeout"), conn)
        actions.append(cmd_deploy(c, ws, path, content, s.get("lang", "bun"),
                                  s.get("summary"), s.get("description"), timeout,
                                  s.get("tag")))

    for sch in m.get("schedules", []):
        actions.append(_provision_schedule(c, ws, sch, url, admin_token))

    return {"folder": folder, "actions": actions}


def _provision_schedule(c, ws, sch, url, admin_token):
    """Ensure a schedule. If `run_as` is set, author it as that user (impersonation)
    so its jobs execute under that identity — the runtime half of folder isolation."""
    path, run_as = sch["path"], sch.get("run_as")
    sc = c
    if run_as:
        try:
            tok = _impersonate(url, admin_token, ws, run_as)
            sc = _client(url, tok)
        except SystemExit:
            return {"schedule": path, "run_as": run_as, "note": "impersonation failed; left unmanaged"}
    try:
        return cmd_schedule_set(sc, ws, path, sch["script"], sch["cron"],
                                sch.get("timezone", "Etc/UTC"), [],
                                not sch.get("enabled", False))
    except SystemExit as e:
        if run_as and e.code in (2, 6):
            return {"schedule": path, "run_as": run_as,
                    "note": "operator cannot author schedules on this instance; enable as admin when wiring cron"}
        raise
    finally:
        if sc is not c:
            sc.close()


# --- CLI ---------------------------------------------------------------------

def main() -> None:
    _gate()                      # every verb passes the project gate first
    _contract(sys.argv[1:])      # contract verbs; domain verbs fall through
    p = argparse.ArgumentParser(
        prog="windmill", description=__doc__,
        formatter_class=argparse.RawDescriptionHelpFormatter)
    p.add_argument("--connection", default=None,
                   help="connection id (optional with a default pointer or a "
                        "sole connection)")
    p.add_argument("--url", default=None, help="Windmill base URL (overrides env/config)")
    p.add_argument("--token", default=None, help="API token (prefer config/env; avoid CLI)")
    p.add_argument("--workspace", default=None, help="workspace id (overrides env/config)")
    p.add_argument("--as", dest="as_user", default=None, metavar="EMAIL",
                   help="act as this workspace user for the call (impersonation via the admin token)")
    sub = p.add_subparsers(dest="cmd", required=True)

    sub.add_parser("help")
    sub.add_parser("doctor")

    sp = sub.add_parser("scripts"); sp.add_argument("--prefix"); sp.add_argument("--limit", type=int, default=100)
    sp = sub.add_parser("script-get"); sp.add_argument("path")
    sp = sub.add_parser("script-delete"); sp.add_argument("path")
    sp = sub.add_parser("deploy")
    sp.add_argument("path"); sp.add_argument("file", help="source file or '-' for stdin")
    sp.add_argument("--lang", default=None, help="bun (default) | deno | python3 | bash | go | nativets")
    sp.add_argument("--summary", default=None); sp.add_argument("--description", default=None)
    sp.add_argument("--timeout", type=int, default=None); sp.add_argument("--tag", default=None)

    sp = sub.add_parser("schedules"); sp.add_argument("--limit", type=int, default=100)
    sp = sub.add_parser("schedule-get"); sp.add_argument("path")
    sp = sub.add_parser("schedule-set")
    sp.add_argument("path"); sp.add_argument("--script", required=True)
    sp.add_argument("--cron", required=True); sp.add_argument("--timezone", default="Etc/UTC")
    sp.add_argument("--arg", action="append", default=[]); sp.add_argument("--off", action="store_true")
    sp = sub.add_parser("schedule-enable"); sp.add_argument("path")
    g = sp.add_mutually_exclusive_group(required=True)
    g.add_argument("--on", action="store_true"); g.add_argument("--off", action="store_true")
    sp = sub.add_parser("schedule-delete"); sp.add_argument("path")

    sp = sub.add_parser("run"); sp.add_argument("path")
    sp.add_argument("--sync", action="store_true"); sp.add_argument("--arg", action="append", default=[])
    sp.add_argument("--timeout", type=int, default=None)
    sp = sub.add_parser("runs"); sp.add_argument("--script"); sp.add_argument("--limit", type=int, default=20)
    sp.add_argument("--running", action="store_true")
    sp.add_argument("--success", action="store_true"); sp.add_argument("--failed", action="store_true")
    sp = sub.add_parser("job"); sp.add_argument("id")

    sp = sub.add_parser("vars"); sp.add_argument("--prefix")
    sp = sub.add_parser("var-set"); sp.add_argument("path")
    sp.add_argument("--value", default=None); sp.add_argument("--stdin", action="store_true")
    sp.add_argument("--plain", action="store_true", help="store non-secret (default is secret)")
    sp.add_argument("--description", default=None)
    sp = sub.add_parser("var-delete"); sp.add_argument("path")

    sp = sub.add_parser("folder-create"); sp.add_argument("name")
    sp.add_argument("--owner", action="append", default=[])
    sp = sub.add_parser("folder-ensure"); sp.add_argument("name")
    sp.add_argument("--owner", action="append", default=[])

    sp = sub.add_parser("triggers"); sp.add_argument("--limit", type=int, default=100)
    sp = sub.add_parser("trigger-get"); sp.add_argument("path")
    sp = sub.add_parser("trigger-set"); sp.add_argument("path")
    sp.add_argument("--script", required=True, help="script/flow path to run (f/..)")
    sp.add_argument("--route", required=True, help="URL route path, no leading / (e.g. inbound/webhook)")
    sp.add_argument("--method", default="post",
                    choices=["get", "post", "put", "delete", "patch"])
    sp.add_argument("--auth", default="none",
                    choices=["none", "windmill", "api_key", "basic_http", "custom_script", "signature"],
                    help="none = public endpoint (default)")
    sp.add_argument("--request-type", dest="request_type", default="sync",
                    choices=["sync", "async", "sync_sse"],
                    help="sync (default) returns the script result; async returns a job id")
    sp.add_argument("--raw", action="store_true",
                    help="pass the body as a raw string (no JSON parse)")
    sp.add_argument("--wrap-body", dest="wrap_body", action="store_true",
                    help="wrap the request body in a 'body' parameter")
    sp.add_argument("--no-workspaced", dest="no_workspaced", action="store_true",
                    help="omit the workspace id from the route URL")
    sp.add_argument("--flow", action="store_true", help="script path points to a flow")
    sp.add_argument("--summary", default=None, help="human label for the trigger")
    sp.add_argument("--description", default=None, help="longer description of the trigger")
    sp.add_argument("--off", action="store_true", help="create disabled")
    sp = sub.add_parser("trigger-delete"); sp.add_argument("path")

    sub.add_parser("datatables")
    sp = sub.add_parser("datatable")
    dsub = sp.add_subparsers(dest="sub", required=True)
    dr = dsub.add_parser("run")
    dr.add_argument("sql", help="SQL text (DDL or DML) to execute")
    dr.add_argument("--store", default="main")
    dr.add_argument("--arg", action="append", default=[],
                    help="extra preview arg key=value (JSON-typed if parseable)")
    dr.add_argument("--timeout", type=int, default=None)
    dt = dsub.add_parser("tables")
    dt.add_argument("--store", default="main")
    ds = dsub.add_parser("schema")
    ds.add_argument("table", help="table name; may be 'schema.table'")
    ds.add_argument("--store", default="main")
    ds.add_argument("--schema", default=None,
                    help="Postgres schema (default: 'public', or the segment "
                         "before the dot in <table>)")

    sp = sub.add_parser("datatable-db")
    ddsub = sp.add_subparsers(dest="sub", required=True)
    ddsub.add_parser("list")
    ddc = ddsub.add_parser("create"); ddc.add_argument("name")
    ddd = ddsub.add_parser("drop"); ddd.add_argument("name")

    sub.add_parser("users")
    sp = sub.add_parser("user-ensure"); sp.add_argument("--email", required=True)
    sp.add_argument("--operator", action="store_true"); sp.add_argument("--admin", action="store_true")
    sp.add_argument("--name", default=None)

    for _name in ("verify", "provision"):
        sp = sub.add_parser(_name)
        sp.add_argument("manifest", nargs="?", default=None,
                        help="optional explicit manifest.json; omit to build from config + --scripts-dir")
        sp.add_argument("--folder", default=None, help="workspace folder/namespace (else WINDMILL_FOLDER)")
        sp.add_argument("--operator", default=None, help="operator user email (else WINDMILL_OPERATOR)")
        sp.add_argument("--operator-name", dest="operator_name", default=None,
                        help="operator display name (else WINDMILL_OPERATOR_NAME)")
        sp.add_argument("--owner", action="append", default=[],
                        help="extra folder owner (u/.. or g/..); the operator is always an owner")
        sp.add_argument("--scripts-dir", dest="scripts_dir", default=None,
                        help="dir of deployable scripts (path f/<folder>/<stem>); omit to skip scripts")

    args = p.parse_args()
    if args.cmd == "help":
        sys.stdout.write((__doc__ or "").lstrip("\n")); return
    if args.cmd == "doctor":
        cmd_doctor(args); return

    conn = _resolve_conn(args)
    # Verbs with sub-verbs (datatable, datatable-db) fold the sub-verb into the
    # gate key so read subs stay ungated and write subs are refused on a
    # read-only connection.
    gate_verb = (f"{args.cmd}:{args.sub}"
                 if args.cmd in ("datatable", "datatable-db") else args.cmd)
    _write_gate(conn["id"], conn["allow_write"], gate_verb)
    url, token, ws = conn["url"], conn["token"], conn["workspace"]
    admin_token = token
    if args.as_user:
        token = _impersonate(url, admin_token, ws, args.as_user)
    with _client(url, token) as c:
        if args.cmd == "scripts":
            _emit(cmd_scripts(c, ws, args.prefix, args.limit))
        elif args.cmd == "script-get":
            _emit(cmd_script_get(c, ws, args.path))
        elif args.cmd == "script-delete":
            _emit(cmd_script_delete(c, ws, args.path))
        elif args.cmd == "deploy":
            timeout = _resolve_deploy_timeout(args.timeout, conn)
            _emit(cmd_deploy(c, ws, args.path, _read_text(args.file), args.lang,
                             args.summary, args.description, timeout, args.tag))
        elif args.cmd == "schedules":
            _emit(cmd_schedules(c, ws, args.limit))
        elif args.cmd == "schedule-get":
            _emit(cmd_schedule_get(c, ws, args.path))
        elif args.cmd == "schedule-set":
            _emit(cmd_schedule_set(c, ws, args.path, args.script, args.cron,
                                   args.timezone, args.arg, args.off))
        elif args.cmd == "schedule-enable":
            _emit(cmd_schedule_enable(c, ws, args.path, args.on and not args.off))
        elif args.cmd == "schedule-delete":
            _emit(cmd_schedule_delete(c, ws, args.path))
        elif args.cmd == "run":
            _emit(cmd_run(c, ws, args.path, args.sync, args.arg, args.timeout))
        elif args.cmd == "runs":
            _emit(cmd_runs(c, ws, args.script, args.limit, args.running, args.success, args.failed))
        elif args.cmd == "job":
            _emit(cmd_job(c, ws, args.id))
        elif args.cmd == "vars":
            _emit(cmd_vars(c, ws, args.prefix))
        elif args.cmd == "var-set":
            if args.value is None and not args.stdin:
                _die(6, "no_value", "var-set needs --value or --stdin")
            value = _read_text(None) if args.stdin else args.value
            _emit(cmd_var_set(c, ws, args.path, value, not args.plain, args.description))
        elif args.cmd == "var-delete":
            _emit(cmd_var_delete(c, ws, args.path))
        elif args.cmd == "folder-create":
            _emit(cmd_folder_create(c, ws, args.name, args.owner))
        elif args.cmd == "folder-ensure":
            _emit(cmd_folder_ensure(c, ws, args.name, args.owner))
        elif args.cmd == "triggers":
            _emit(cmd_triggers(c, ws, args.limit))
        elif args.cmd == "trigger-get":
            _emit(cmd_trigger_get(c, ws, args.path))
        elif args.cmd == "trigger-set":
            _emit(cmd_trigger_set(c, ws, url, args.path, args.script, args.route,
                                  args.method, args.auth, args.request_type, args.raw,
                                  args.wrap_body, not args.no_workspaced, args.flow,
                                  args.summary, args.description, args.off))
        elif args.cmd == "trigger-delete":
            _emit(cmd_trigger_delete(c, ws, args.path))
        elif args.cmd == "datatables":
            _emit(cmd_datatables(c, ws))
        elif args.cmd == "datatable":
            if args.sub == "run":
                _emit(cmd_datatable_run(c, ws, args.sql, args.store, args.arg, args.timeout))
            elif args.sub == "tables":
                _emit(cmd_datatable_tables(c, ws, args.store))
            elif args.sub == "schema":
                _emit(cmd_datatable_schema(c, ws, args.table, args.store, args.schema))
        elif args.cmd == "datatable-db":
            if args.sub == "list":
                _emit(cmd_datatable_db_list(c))
            elif args.sub == "create":
                _emit(cmd_datatable_db_create(c, args.name))
            elif args.sub == "drop":
                _emit(cmd_datatable_db_drop(c, args.name))
        elif args.cmd == "users":
            _emit(cmd_users(c, ws))
        elif args.cmd == "user-ensure":
            _emit(cmd_user_ensure(c, ws, args.email, args.operator, args.admin, args.name))
        elif args.cmd in ("verify", "provision"):
            m, base = (_load_manifest(args.manifest) if args.manifest
                       else _config_manifest(args))
            if args.cmd == "verify":
                _emit(cmd_verify(c, ws, m, base))
            else:
                _emit(cmd_provision(c, ws, m, base, url, admin_token, conn))


if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
